The paper deals with experimental economics and data mining to extract deterministic regularities in human strategic behavior. The most relevant sub-category is cs.GT (Game Theory and Decision Science), which deals with the study of strategic interactions between agents. The paper also involves data mining techniques, which makes cs.LG (Machine Learning) a likely sub-category. The use of alternative models in experimental economics suggests cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as another possible sub-category. The paper also involves the analysis of datasets, which makes cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a likely sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the fusion of experimental economics and data mining, which suggests cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) as a possible sub-category.
